    "recap_headline": "University of Minnesota Athletics",
    "recap_text": "BLOOMINGTON, IND. \u2013\nThe University of Minnesota baseball team played out their weekend series finale against Indiana University today, taking down the Hoosiers 14-2 in eight innings on the road at Bart Kaufman Field.\nMarcus Kruzan\ngot the win for Minnesota, tossing 3.2 shutout innings and striking out three.\nBen Gregory\nalso pitched well, going three innings and striking out three.\nJack Spanier\nwent 4-for-5 today, including a triple, a home run, and five RBIs to lead the Gophers.\nTy Allen\nput together a standout performance at the plate as well, going 2-for-5 with a home run and three RBIs.\nWeber Neels\nalso chipped in for Minnesota, putting together three hits in four trips to the plate while adding a home run and two RBIs.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nThe Gophers jumped out to an early lead in the first inning, tallying the first runs of the game on a two run home run from\nWeber Neels\n.\nMinnesota picked up where they left off in the second, tallying three more runs on a three run home run over the left field wall from\nTy Allen\n. The Gophers picked up one more run before the end of the inning on a bases loaded walk, capturing a 6-0 advantage heading into the third.\nThe Gophers continued to push the advantage in the third and fourth, adding two runs over the next two innings on a pair of RBI singles off the bats of\nJack Spanier\nand\nJameson Martin\n.\nThe Hoosiers got their first run on the board in the fifth on an RBI groundout before Minnesota continued to stack on the runs in the seventh inning when Spanier added a two run home run to his day, making it a 10-1 lead for the Gophers.\nMinnesota added four more runs in the eighth inning to push to a double digit lead. The Gophers scored on a wild pitch before adding one run on a sacrifice fly from\nSam Hunt\nand another two runs on a standup triple from Spanier.\nIndiana picked up one run in their half of the eighth before the game came to a close, with the Gophers picking up the 14-2 mercy rule victory to close out the weekend.\nGAME NOTES\n\u00bb Minnesota's highest scoring inning was the eighth, when it pushed four runs across.\n\u00bb Minnesota took a 2-0 lead in the top half of the first and didn't surrender that lead for the remainder of the game.\n\u00bb Minnesota hitters hit three homers in the ballgame.\n\u00bb The Gophers out-hit the Hoosiers at a 14-6 clip.\n\u00bb\nCharlie Sutherland\nand\nJameson Martin\nboth stole two bases in the game.\n\u00bb The Gophers stole seven bases as a team.\n\u00bb Minnesota went 5-for-15 (.333) with runners in scoring position.\n\u00bb Minnesota pitchers limited Indiana to just 1-for-5 (.200) with runners in scoring position.\n\u00bb Minnesota pitchers faced 31 Indiana hitters in the game, allowing 10 ground balls and eight fly balls while striking out six.\n\u00bb The Gophers drew six walks from Indiana pitching.\n\u00bb Spanier led the Gophers at the plate, going 4 for 5 with a triple, a home run and five RBIs.",
